Right?

00:09:23.979 --> 00:09:24.979
And I'm going to help you.

00:09:24.979 --> 00:09:29.179
You know, we're going to just do it all over in R. The philosophy that I have adopted after

00:09:29.179 --> 00:09:34.940
failing miserably at that and basically being told to go sod off is help people take the

00:09:34.940 --> 00:09:41.219
hard parts, the high friction parts, and build some automation around that.

00:09:41.219 --> 00:09:44.500
Don't feel like we have to change someone's life completely.

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:46.940
Make an incremental change.

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:51.900
We've started in my team calling this the 10% better approach rather than trying to

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:54.239
completely fix a workflow.

00:09:54.239 --> 00:09:56.979
Every time we do it, we try to make it 10% better.

00:09:56.979 --> 00:10:01.940
We have made more progress through the 10% improvement approach than we have through

00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:07.179
any number of projects that were grandiose and ultimately failed because the scope was

00:10:07.179 --> 00:10:08.219
too big.

00:10:08.219 --> 00:10:12.780
So I can make anything I do 10% better.

