00:14:11.799 --> 00:14:17.179
We had a logical fallacy in my team for a long time, or at least I perceive it as a

00:14:17.179 --> 00:14:18.500
logical fallacy.

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:25.380
We looked at this, and this is the whole, if it takes a long time to automate a task,

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:29.900
but it doesn't save you a lot of time, don't do it, kind of seems obvious.

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:33.900
Well, this illustration, like so many things, is a model.

00:14:33.900 --> 00:14:37.020
That's a model of reality that isn't actually reality.

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:38.020
And it's wrong.

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:39.419
Because all models are wrong by definition.

00:14:39.419 --> 00:14:42.460
They're actually fairly useful to the extent the assumptions hold.

00:14:42.460 --> 00:14:46.700
Let me tell you a few of the assumptions that are wrong with this image.

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:50.979
So one of the assumptions is all time is of equal value.

00:14:50.979 --> 00:14:57.539
So we can't take, you know, five hours to fix this because it doesn't save us that much

00:14:57.539 --> 00:14:58.539
time.

00:14:58.539 --> 00:15:02.260
It doesn't save us five hours over the course of some time period.

00:15:02.260 --> 00:15:06.619
The fallacy there in my world is unequal time value.

00:15:06.619 --> 00:15:11.780
So right around the end of the quarter, we have a flurry of reporting activity.

00:15:11.780 --> 00:15:14.460
And that time is incredibly precious.

00:15:15.219 --> 00:15:17.700
August, however, nobody's there.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:19.539
Who cares what we do in August, right?

00:15:19.539 --> 00:15:21.659
So we can take time in August.

00:15:21.659 --> 00:15:27.900
And if we can save a few minutes or a few hours during our very, very busy period, that's

00:15:27.900 --> 00:15:28.900
a great return.

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:33.340
And it's because our time isn't of equal value.

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:37.820
The other thing is the current frequency of reporting is what we would want to do in the

00:15:37.820 --> 00:15:38.820
future.

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:40.659
And we have found this not to be the case at all.

00:15:40.659 --> 00:15:44.619
Because we have automated things, we discover we run them more often and we want to run

00:15:44.619 --> 00:15:45.820
them more often.

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:49.539
We want to get the analysis that we thought we only needed once a quarter.

00:15:49.539 --> 00:15:53.419
Oh, if we can get that daily, well, that might change how we do things.

00:15:53.419 --> 00:15:57.619
So it ends up not being stationary.

00:15:57.619 --> 00:16:02.140
All time spent doing analytics is of equal utility.

00:16:02.140 --> 00:16:09.739
Some tasks are so awful and tedious that your analysts will quit and go work to Facebook

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:12.020
instead of doing them, right?

00:16:12.020 --> 00:16:13.539
Don't make your analysts run away.

00:16:13.539 --> 00:16:16.299
Help them automate those manual processes.

00:16:16.299 --> 00:16:22.020
Not because they take a long time, but because they suck their joy.

00:16:22.020 --> 00:16:26.219
And the other assumption that's fallacious is that automated and manual workflows produce

00:16:26.219 --> 00:16:28.979
the same product.

00:16:28.979 --> 00:16:30.099
This is not the case.

00:16:30.099 --> 00:16:37.619
The product produced out of a automated process should be more accurate if you're doing it,

00:16:37.619 --> 00:16:38.619
right?

